04721nam a22007455i 9780813563664DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20152015nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2014040075  a97808135636647 a10.36019/97808135636642doi  a(DE-B1597)526347  a(OCoLC)944303842  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aDS143b.P565 2015 7aREL0000002bisacsh04a305.89240732231 aPianko, Noam, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJewish Peoplehood :bAn American Innovation /cNoam Pianko. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (186 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aKey Words in Jewish Studies ;v60 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWinner of the 2017 American Jewish Historical Society’s Saul Viener Book Prize Although fewer American Jews today describe themselves as religious, they overwhelmingly report a strong sense of belonging to the Jewish people. Indeed, Jewish peoplehood has eclipsed religion—as well as ethnicity and nationality—as the essence of what binds Jews around the globe to one another. In Jewish Peoplehood, Noam Pianko highlights the current significance and future relevance of “peoplehood” by tracing the rise, transformation, and return of this novel term. The book tells the surprising story of peoplehood. Though it evokes a sense of timelessness, the term actually emerged in the United States in the 1930s, where it was introduced by American Jewish leaders, most notably Rabbi Stephen Wise and Rabbi Mordecai Kaplan, with close ties to the Zionist movement. It engendered a sense of unity that transcended religious differences, cultural practices, geographic distance, economic disparity, and political divides, fostering solidarity with other Jews facing common existential threats, including the Holocaust, and establishing a closer connection to the Jewish homeland. But today, Pianko points out, as globalization erodes the dominance of nationalism in shaping collective identity, Jewish peoplehood risks becoming an outdated paradigm. He explains why popular models of peoplehood fail to address emerging conceptions of ethnicity, nationalism, and race, and he concludes with a much-needed roadmap for a radical reconfiguration of Jewish collectivity in an increasingly global era. Innovative and provocative, Jewish Peoplehood provides fascinating insight into a term that assumes an increasingly important position at the heart of American Jewish and Israeli life. For additional information go to: http://www.noampianko.net  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aIsrael and the diaspora. 0aJewsxIdentity. 0aJewszUnited StatesxIdentity. 0aJewszUnited StatesxPolitics and governmenty21st century. 0aJewszUnited StatesxSocial conditionsy21st century. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh1 aBush, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDash Moore, Deborah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoore, MacDonald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066615140uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081356366440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813563664423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780813563664/original  a978-3-11-066615-1  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK